item.content:encoded:
A very valuable reference in this respect seems Alfonzo and Peterson 2006. They highlight 3 main complications in estimating demand systems from household survey data:
<ol>
	<li><strong>Quality bias</strong>: due to the usually large number of expenditure items one needs to aggregate the items into fewer groups. These groups necessarily include items of different quality. The observed choice of the aggregate items then reflects choice of quantity and quality. Thus, obtaining simple unit values = value / quantity as prices results in bias by quality and they need to be corrected for that.</li>
	<li><strong>Measurement errors</strong>: Recorded expenditures and quantities contain error since they rely on human recall of past purchases.</li>
	<li><strong>Zero purchases</strong>: Not every household buys every item and thus surveys report zero purchases which might be either systematic or non-systematic. To account for this, a limited dependent variable approach is required.</li>
</ol>
They show how to correct prices for quality.

Alfonzo, L. &amp; Peterson, H. H., Estimating food demand in Paraguay from household survey data Agricultural Economics, 2006, 34, 243-257
