In order to programmatically add equations to a GAMS model, these equations have to be generated in the preprocessing phase. It seems best to loop through sets and write out the required code with PUT command before including the new file using $include.

This example simulates nested sets and displays the contents of the 2nd level sets.

PERENNIAL / A, B /
ANNUAL / C, D, E /
ASL1    set of activity aggregates for level 1
/
PERENNIAL
ANNUAL
/
;
file test /test.gms/;
put test;
test.lw = 0;
test.nw = 0;
LOOP(ASL1,
put "DISPLAY ", ASL1.tl, ";" /
);
$include test.gms

The following code will result in two equations which each involves a sum over a different subset.
<blockquote>
<pre>SETs
  S / A,B,C /
  SS / SS1, SS2 /
  SN(SS,S) / SS1.(A,B), SS2.(C) /;
PARAMETER
  z(S) / A 5, B 7, C 3/;
VARIABLE
  X(SS);
EQUATIONS
  EQ(SS);
EQ(SS)..
  X(SS) =E= sum(S$SN(SS,S), z(S));
MODEL test / EQ /;
SOLVE test using MCP;
DISPLAY X.L;</pre>
</blockquote>

